div.p: This page provides a list of the FHIR artifacts defined as part of this implementation guide.
Profiles for mapping 11073 20601 Personal Health Devices to FHIR resources
Value Sets used and defined in this Implementation Guide
Code Systems defined in this Implementation Guide
Capability Statements defined in this Implementation Guide
Examples of resources following the Implementation Guide Profiles

td.a: • Example of a first time Bundle upload

tr.td: This example shows a full transaction Bundle containing Patient, Device, and Observation resources. In subsequent uploads, the Patient and Device resources would not need to be present.
This example PHD Device resource is referenced by other examples and is present for the validator.

This example is an upload from a Bluetooth Low Energy Pulse oximeter device streaming data. In this case the gateway has previously uploaded measurements and saved the logical ids of the Patient and Device resources so they are not re-uploaded.

This example is a simple numeric observation of a pulse rate from a pulse oximeter. This particular example also has a component as the original measurement has a Supplemental Types attribute indicating that this is a SPOT measurement (a stable average).
This example is an RTSA observation of a pleth signal from a pulse oximeter. This very short waveform maps to a valueSampledData element.
This example contains a NaN (not a number) measurement.

This example contains measurement that is itself a code. The measurement comes from a Glucose meter and indicates that the glucose measurement was taken after lunch or dinner. It is also known as the meal context.

td.a: • Example of a ASN1 BITs measurement

tr.td: This example is a device and sensor status measurement from a pulse oximeter. This measurement indicates one or more issues the sensor had attempting to take the measurement, for example, finger poorly positioned, cannot get a sufficiently strong signal, etc.
This example is from a Blood Pressure cuff.
This example is some arbitrary text from a Glucose meter explaining the failure of the measurement.

td.a: • Example of a Coincident Time Stamp

tr.td: This example is a Coincident Time stamp where the PHG is better synchronized to NTP time than the PHD. This situation is the most prevalent.

td.a: • Example of a Coincident Time Stamp with a Time Fault

tr.td: This example is a Coincident Time stamp where the PHD has a time fault; it's current time line is unknown and it reported time stamps in its measurements.

td.a: • Example of a Blood Pressure PHD

tr.td: This example maps the MDS data from a Blood Pressure PHD. This device did not report Reg-Cert-Data-List information.

td.a: • Example of a Glucose Monitor PHD

tr.td: This example maps an Glucose monitor PHD. It is referenced by a coded Glucose meal context observation

td.a: • Example of a Coincident Time Stamp

tr.td: This Coincident Time Stamp observation is referenced by the Blood Pressure Observation

td.a: • Example of a Coincident Time Stamp referenced by the Glucose Meal Context Observation

tr.td: This Coincident Time Stamp observation is referenced by the the Glucose meal context Observation
This example maps an Android Gateway
This example maps a patient where an optional patient name is included
